summary:
The child’s acute gastroenteritis followed by progressive neurologic decline strongly suggests post-infectious Guillain-Barré Syndrome (GBS). Key supporting features include molecular mimicry triggered by prior gut infection and the presence of albuminocytologic dissociation—increased CSF protein with normal white blood cells—which characterizes GBS pathology.

\boxed{D}

The correct laboratory finding that supports diagnosis of post-infectious Guillain-Barré Syndrome is an increase in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) protein with a normal white blood cell count—a phenomenon called albuminocytologic dissociation resulting from autoimmunity against nerve tissue after preceding gastrointestinal infection. Given the timeline between intestinal illness and development of symmetric limb weakness and reduced reflexes, this result best explains the patient's condition among available options.

